<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="131" pageId="3" pageNumber="130" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,546,2011]" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1734,1759]" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">Etymology.</emphasis>
It is a pleasure to name the new species in honor of Prof. Dr. Albino Morimasa 
<taxonomicName authority="Quintas &amp; Felix &amp; Lima &amp; Mejdalani, 2017" authorityName="Quintas &amp; Felix &amp; Lima &amp; Mejdalani" authorityYear="2017" box="[1311,1436,1734,1759]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sakakibara" status="sp. nov.">Sakakibara</taxonomicName>
(Departamento de Zoologia, Setor de Ciências Biológicas, Universidade Federal do 
<collectingRegion box="[1111,1189,1771,1795]" country="Brazil" name="Parana" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">Paraná</collectingRegion>
) in recognition of his outstanding contribution to our knowledge of the Neotropical treehoppers. The species epithet is a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,546,2011]" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,408,1878,1903]" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">Taxonomic notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Quintas &amp; Felix &amp; Lima &amp; Mejdalani, 2017" authorityName="Quintas &amp; Felix &amp; Lima &amp; Mejdalani" authorityYear="2017" box="[416,698,1878,1902]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sakakibara" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[416,698,1878,1902]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">Dilobopterus sakakibara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[706,797,1878,1903]" pageId="3" pageNumber="130" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[706,797,1878,1903]" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Signoret, 1853" authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1853" box="[1012,1351,1878,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trinotatus">
<emphasis box="[1012,1157,1879,1902]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">D. trinotatus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Signoret" box="[1173,1342,1878,1903]" pageId="3" pageNumber="130" refString="Signoret, V. (1853) Revue iconographique des Tettigonides. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, 1, 323 - 374, pls. 8 - 12." type="journal article" year="1853">Signoret, 1853</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Signoret, 1853" authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1853" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="segmentalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">D. segmentalis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Signoret" box="[298,470,1914,1939]" pageId="3" pageNumber="130" refString="Signoret, V. (1853) Revue iconographique des Tettigonides. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, 1, 323 - 374, pls. 8 - 12." type="journal article" year="1853">Signoret, 1853</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. These three species share the presence of conspicuous setae on the apical portion of the paraphyses rami (
<figureCitation box="[411,511,1950,1975]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 16" captionStartId="4.[151,263,1434,1457]" captionTargetBox="[184,1434,391,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[152,1435,375,1412]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 16. Dilobopterus sakakibara sp. nov. 9, head, pronotum, and mesonotum, dorsal view (male paratype). 10, forewing. 11 – 16, male genitalia. 11, pygofer, lateral view. 12, valve and subgenital plate, ventral view. 13, connective and style, dorsal view. 14, ejaculatory reservoir and aedeagus, lateral view. 15, paraphyses, laterodorsal view (setae of one ramus omitted). 16, paraphyses, dorsal view. Scale bars: 9 = 1 mm, 10 = 2 mm, 11 – 16 = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/816001/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">Figs. 15</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[530,561,1951,1975]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 25" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1088,1111]" captionTargetBox="[171,1409,187,1065]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1436,163,1082]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 25. Dilobopterus segmentalis (Signoret, 1853). 17, head, pronotum, and mesonotum, dorsal view. 18 – 24, male genitalia. 18, pygofer, lateral view. 19, pygofer ventral margin (arrow indicates location of small dentiform process), ventral view. 20, valve and subgenital plate, ventral view. 21, connective and style, dorsal view. 22, ejaculatory reservoir, aedeagus, and basal segment of anal tube, lateral view. 23, paraphyses, laterodorsal view (setae of one ramus omitted). 24, paraphyses, dorsal view. 25, apical portion of female abdomen, ventral view. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/816003/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">23</figureCitation>
). This is a peculiar feature that suggests that they form a group within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1850" box="[151,299,1987,2011]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,299,1987,2011]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">Dilobopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which we herein call the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1853" box="[589,698,1987,2010]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trinotatus">
<emphasis box="[589,698,1987,2010]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">trinotatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. The new species (
<figureCitation box="[982,1063,1986,2011]" captionStart="FIGURES 26 – 29" captionStartId="6.[151,263,1653,1676]" captionTargetBox="[184,1378,948,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,916,1632]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 26 – 29. Body in dorsal view (antennae and legs not depicted). 26, Dilobopterus nelsoni sp. nov., male holotype (total length 6.7 mm). 27, D. sakakibara sp. nov., male holotype (t. l. 6.9 mm). 28, D. segmentalis (Signoret, 1853), male (t. l. 9.0 mm). 29, D. trinotatus (Signoret, 1853), female (t. l. 9.0 mm). The last three species belong to the trinotatus group (see text for details)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/816005/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) shares with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1853" box="[1210,1376,1987,2011]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="segmentalis">
<emphasis box="[1210,1376,1987,2011]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">D. segmentalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1390,1436,1986,2011]" captionStart="FIGURES 26 – 29" captionStartId="6.[151,263,1653,1676]" captionTargetBox="[184,1378,948,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,916,1632]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 26 – 29. Body in dorsal view (antennae and legs not depicted). 26, Dilobopterus nelsoni sp. nov., male holotype (total length 6.7 mm). 27, D. sakakibara sp. nov., male holotype (t. l. 6.9 mm). 28, D. segmentalis (Signoret, 1853), male (t. l. 9.0 mm). 29, D. trinotatus (Signoret, 1853), female (t. l. 9.0 mm). The last three species belong to the trinotatus group (see text for details)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/816005/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">Fig.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">
28) the presence of a large subrectangular vitreous area on the basal half of the forewings, which allows the observation of large transverse yellow areas of the abdominal tergum. In the new species, the pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[1350,1431,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 16" captionStartId="4.[151,263,1434,1457]" captionTargetBox="[184,1434,391,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[152,1435,375,1412]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 16. Dilobopterus sakakibara sp. nov. 9, head, pronotum, and mesonotum, dorsal view (male paratype). 10, forewing. 11 – 16, male genitalia. 11, pygofer, lateral view. 12, valve and subgenital plate, ventral view. 13, connective and style, dorsal view. 14, ejaculatory reservoir and aedeagus, lateral view. 15, paraphyses, laterodorsal view (setae of one ramus omitted). 16, paraphyses, dorsal view. Scale bars: 9 = 1 mm, 10 = 2 mm, 11 – 16 = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/816001/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Figs. 9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,180,224,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 26 – 29" captionStartId="6.[151,263,1653,1676]" captionTargetBox="[184,1378,948,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,916,1632]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 26 – 29. Body in dorsal view (antennae and legs not depicted). 26, Dilobopterus nelsoni sp. nov., male holotype (total length 6.7 mm). 27, D. sakakibara sp. nov., male holotype (t. l. 6.9 mm). 28, D. segmentalis (Signoret, 1853), male (t. l. 9.0 mm). 29, D. trinotatus (Signoret, 1853), female (t. l. 9.0 mm). The last three species belong to the trinotatus group (see text for details)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/816005/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">27</figureCitation>
) is dark brown and has two transverse rows of four yellow spots near the anterior margin, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1853" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="segmentalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">D. segmentalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the pronotal disc (
<figureCitation box="[500,595,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 25" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1088,1111]" captionTargetBox="[171,1409,187,1065]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1436,163,1082]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 25. Dilobopterus segmentalis (Signoret, 1853). 17, head, pronotum, and mesonotum, dorsal view. 18 – 24, male genitalia. 18, pygofer, lateral view. 19, pygofer ventral margin (arrow indicates location of small dentiform process), ventral view. 20, valve and subgenital plate, ventral view. 21, connective and style, dorsal view. 22, ejaculatory reservoir, aedeagus, and basal segment of anal tube, lateral view. 23, paraphyses, laterodorsal view (setae of one ramus omitted). 24, paraphyses, dorsal view. 25, apical portion of female abdomen, ventral view. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/816003/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Figs. 17</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[609,638,260,284]" captionStart="FIGURES 26 – 29" captionStartId="6.[151,263,1653,1676]" captionTargetBox="[184,1378,948,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,916,1632]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 26 – 29. Body in dorsal view (antennae and legs not depicted). 26, Dilobopterus nelsoni sp. nov., male holotype (total length 6.7 mm). 27, D. sakakibara sp. nov., male holotype (t. l. 6.9 mm). 28, D. segmentalis (Signoret, 1853), male (t. l. 9.0 mm). 29, D. trinotatus (Signoret, 1853), female (t. l. 9.0 mm). The last three species belong to the trinotatus group (see text for details)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/816005/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">28</figureCitation>
) has a large greenish-yellow or green central area, dark brown lateral and posterior margins, and irregular dark brown to black marks near the anterior margin.
</paragraph>
